issue(id="0009" status="open")
  title Introduce clean/dirty module naming and stack composition for scrubs guests
  user-story
    as-a scrubs maintainer evolving guest customization
    i-want guest extensions organized as boundary-aware modules composed into named stacks
    so-that reusable guest behavior stays legible, safer to review, and easier to mix without burying too much policy inside one-off guest shims
  premise.
    Scrubs currently has an extension layer for per-guest accommodations, but
    its shape is still too close to ad hoc shims. That makes reuse possible,
    yet it does not clearly communicate whether a given capability belongs to
    clean space, dirty space, or a one-off guest policy. Over time, that
    ambiguity risks pulling too much meaning into guest-local override files
    and making the trust boundary harder to audit.

    The desired direction is a clearer composition model. Reusable building
    blocks should be named for the space they support, such as
    `clean-docker.nix`, `clean-gcloud.nix`, or `dirty-postgres.nix`, and
    named stack directories should compose those modules into coherent guest
    profiles. Bootstrap should then be able to bring up either a plain default
    guest or a guest shaped by a selected stack, with an ergonomic lookup path
    that does not require every repo to own the whole machine definition.
  acceptance-criteria
    criterion Scrubs has a documented guest-extension model based on named stacks rather than loosely named per-project shims.
    criterion Reusable guest modules are named to reflect the trust boundary they support, so clean-space and dirty-space responsibilities are explicit in the filename and intent.
    criterion At least one composed stack demonstrates that multiple reusable modules can be combined without collapsing their trust-boundary meaning into a monolithic guest file.
    criterion Bootstrap has a clear operator path for launching a plain default guest and for launching a guest from a selected stack.
    criterion The resulting layout is documented well enough that future maintainers can add a new clean or dirty capability without guessing where it belongs.
  review-items
    item(status="open").
      Decide whether bootstrap should prefer implicit stack lookup by instance
      name, require an explicit stack flag, or support both with a predictable
      precedence rule.
    item(status="open").
      Decide which existing guest customizations should graduate into reusable
      modules first, and which ones should stay stack-local because they encode
      product-specific policy rather than reusable capability.
    item(status="open").
      Decide whether any legacy shim path should remain as a temporary
      compatibility layer during the migration or whether the rename should be
      intentionally breaking and cleaned up in one pass.
    item(status="open").
      Make sure the module naming scheme continues to optimize for boundary
      readability rather than drifting into generic names that hide whether a
      tool belongs to clean space or dirty space.
